Here's the proper approach using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`**, handle the app sleep/resume:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackground;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppForeground;

        // Restore any saved draft on load
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void OnAppBackground(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppForeground(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        string saved = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(saved) && string.IsNullOrEmpty(NoteEditor.Text))
            NoteEditor.Text = saved;
    }

    // Clear the draft when the user explicitly saves
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }

    // Unsubscribe to avoid leaks
    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackground;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated -= OnAppForeground;
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** — lightweight key-value store, ideal for small text drafts. For large content, use `SecureStorage` or file I/O instead.
- **`Deactivated`/`Activated`** — fire when the app loses/gains focus (background/foreground).
- **Unsubscribe in `OnDisappearing`** to prevent memory leaks.
- **Call `ClearDraft()`** in your save button handler so stale drafts don't reappear.
